---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { base } from '../../../utils/base.js';
---
<BaseLayout title="Torino: Relocation Suitability — Technical Deep Dive - Nico">
  <div class="page-container">
    <div class="case-study">
      <header class="case-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study — Torino Relocation Suitability</p>
        <h1>Technical Deep Dive</h1>
        <p class="intro">
          This page documents the pipeline behind the
          <a class="inline-link" href={`${base}/en/case-study-torino/`}> Torino case study </a>
          in full: the PostGIS schema, the exact QNEAT3 parameters used for
          every isochrone, the classification methods, and the limitations
          that were stated — not corrected retroactively — throughout the
          analysis. It's written for anyone evaluating the methodology
          directly rather than taking the Overview's narrative at face
          value.
        </p>
        <p class="aside">
          Source code:{' '}
          <a class="inline-link" href="https://github.com/antonio-nico-santos/gis-portfolio" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            github.com/antonio-nico-santos/gis-portfolio
          </a>
        </p>
      </header>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study">
      <section class="methodology">

        <article class="step">
          <h2>1. Data pipeline and database schema</h2>
          <p>
            All analysis data lives in a single PostgreSQL/PostGIS database
            (<code>relocation</code>), in a dedicated <code>torino </code> 
            schema. Every geometry is stored in <strong>EPSG:32632</strong>
            (WGS 84 / UTM zone 32N) rather than WGS 84 lat/lon — a fixed,
            projected CRS in meters is what makes distance and area
            calculations (buffers, isochrone raster cell size, choropleth
            area) valid in the first place; degrees aren't a usable unit for
            that math.
          </p>
          <table class="spec-table">
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Table</th><th>Geometry</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><code>omi_zones</code></td>
                <td>MultiPolygonZ</td>
                <td>47 OMI real-estate zones, with published rent bands (min/max by property condition) and a derived <code>affito</code> column — the estimated-rent figure actually used downstream, not the raw OMI range</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>torino_confini</code></td>
                <td>MultiPolygon</td>
                <td>Administrative boundary of the comune, carrying ISTAT-style codes (province, region, comune) used to clip and label the other layers</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>vie_torino</code></td>
                <td>LineString</td>
                <td>Road network extracted via OSMnx, including the routing topology QNEAT3's Dijkstra-based solver needs (<code>u</code>, <code>v</code>, <code>key</code> from the source OSMnx/NetworkX multigraph; <code>source</code>, <code>target</code> as reindexed integer node IDs)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>asili_nido</code></td>
                <td>Point</td>
                <td>Nurseries sourced from Google Places, extended with availability-tracking fields (<code>disponibilita</code>, <code>dispn_da</code>) and cost fields (<code>cost_full</code>, <code>cost_matut</code>, <code>cost_vesp</code>, <code>cost_iscrz</code>) updated by hand as replies came in from the 100+ nurseries contacted by email</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>farmacia</code>, <code>palestra</code>, <code>parco_giochi</code>, <code>supermercato</code>, <code>stazione</code></td>
                <td>Point</td>
                <td>Uniform Google Places POI tables (pharmacies, gyms, playgrounds, supermarkets, stations) — service-context layers for step 1/3 of the Overview</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>appartamento</code></td>
                <td>Point</td>
                <td>Working table for candidate listings: price, size, condominium/utilities/parking costs, nursery proximity and cost, plus negotiation fields (contact name, phone, exact address, free-text comments, a priority flag). None of this is published as-is — the anonymized 15-row A–O table on the Overview page is derived from it, with every one of those identifying columns stripped</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p>
            <strong>View</strong> <code>nido_disponibile</code> — nurseries
            filtered to <code>disponibilita = 'SI'</code>, ordered by
            <code> cost_full</code>. This was the working shortlist consulted
            while responses were still arriving by email, not a separate
            export.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Indexing:</strong> every geometry column carries a GiST
            spatial index — required once isochrone generation and spatial
            joins are running against a road network with thousands of
            edges.
          </p>
          <p>
            The pedestrian network used for the nursery isochrones (step 4)
            isn't a separate table in this schema — it came from a second, 
            <code> network_type='walk'</code> OSMnx query (distinct from the
            <code> drive</code>-type graph behind <code>vie_torino</code>)
            and was carried through QNEAT3 as a QGIS layer rather than
            persisted to PostGIS.
          </p>
          <p class="callout">
            <strong>Declared limitation:</strong> no foreign keys. Zone
            membership on <code>asili_nido</code> (<code>omi_zone</code>,
            <code> cod_zone</code>) is a denormalized text match against
            <code> omi_zones</code>, not an enforced relationship — workable
            for a single-analyst dataset built iteratively over a few
            weeks, but it means referential integrity was never checked
            automatically. A renamed or resplit zone in
            <code> omi_zones</code> wouldn't have propagated. Stated here
            rather than fixed after the fact, for the same reason the other
            limits on this page are: the goal is an accurate record of the
            process actually used, not a retroactively idealized one.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>2. Road network and speed model</h2>
          <p>
            Extracted via OSMnx and loaded into <code>vie_torino</code>.
            Since per-segment real-world speed data isn't consistently
            available, travel speed is assigned by OSM road classification:
          </p>
          <pre class="spec-block">motorway    130 km/h
trunk       110 km/h
primary      90 km/h
secondary    70 km/h
tertiary     50 km/h
residential  30 km/h</pre>
          <p>
            This same table, filtered to <code>highway = 'footway'</code>,
            is the walking-network case referenced throughout this page —
            not stored separately, filtered per analysis.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>3. Commute isochrones <span class="step-ref">(step 2 of the Overview)</span></h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Tool:</strong> QGIS QNEAT3, algorithm <em>Iso-Area as
            Interpolation (from Layer)</em>, run once per work site
            (Luserna San Giovanni, the Aosta-area site, Moncalieri).
          </p>
          <pre class="spec-block">CELL_SIZE:      5
STRATEGY:       1        (Fastest Path — time, not distance)
SPEED_FIELD:    maxspeed_finale
DEFAULT_SPEED:  5         (fallback value, network-entry cost)
MAX_DIST:       25000
TOLERANCE:      5</pre>
          <p>
            Output units are <strong>seconds</strong> — confirmed
            empirically by checking one raster pixel against a known real
            travel time, since QNEAT3 doesn't document this clearly itself.
          </p>
          <p><strong>Post-processing:</strong></p>
          <ol class="spec-list">
            <li>Clip each site's raster to the Torino boundary (<code>torino_confini</code>).</li>
            <li>Combine with Raster Calculator into a weighted weekly-commute figure: <code>(chatillon × 2) + (luserna × 2) + (moncalieri × 1)</code> — weights are assumed weekly visit frequency per site, not priority.</li>
            <li>Divide by 60 to convert seconds to minutes.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            <strong>Classification:</strong> Equal Interval, 4 classes,
            thresholds set manually after inspecting the histogram rather
            than computed automatically —
            <code>&lt; 200 min</code>, <code>200–210 min</code>,
            <code>210–220 min</code>, <code>&gt; 220 min</code>.
          </p>
          <p class="callout">
            <strong>Known limitation, stated deliberately:</strong> the
            network is treated as undirected — no handling of one-way
            restrictions — and real traffic (peak hours, congestion) isn't
            modeled. Adequate for regional-scale comparison between
            neighborhoods, not for street-level routing. Real commute times
            are likely underestimated.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>4. Local services and nursery data collection <span class="step-ref">(step 3)</span></h2>
          <p>
            OpenStreetMap's coverage of nurseries, markets, gyms,
            playgrounds, and pharmacies was too sparse for this to work, so
            all POI data came from the Google Places API instead — queried
            in sub-areas to stay under its per-query result cap, covering
            both Torino and Pinerolo (the real alternative ruled out in
            step 5). Results were cleaned with an AOI filter and duplicate
            removal (duplicates are expected at sub-area boundaries), then
            loaded into PostGIS.
          </p>
          <p>
            Nursery availability specifically isn't something an API
            returns — it came from directly emailing 100+ nurseries and
            updating <code>asili_nido.disponibilita</code> in PostGIS as
            replies arrived, using the <code>nido_disponibile</code> view
            as a running shortlist.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>5. Pedestrian isochrones from available nurseries <span class="step-ref">(step 4)</span></h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Tool:</strong> QNEAT3, <em>Iso-Area as Contours (from
            Layer)</em> and <em>Iso-Area as Polygons (from Layer)</em>,
            multiple sources (nurseries with confirmed availability only).
          </p>
          <pre class="spec-block">Optimization Criterion:  Shortest Path (distance, not time)
Network:                 pedestrian graph (OSMnx, network_type='walk')</pre>
          <p>
            <strong>Bands:</strong> exact isolines at 200 / 400 / 600 / 800
            / 1000 m — these are contour lines, not ranges, so the correct
            legend label is the exact value of each line, not an interval.
          </p>
          <p class="callout">
            <strong>A deliberate methodological choice:</strong> distance
            instead of time. Walking time with a toddler is too variable
            to be a reliable metric, so this uses shortest-path distance
            rather than the fastest-path time model applied to the commute
            step above — a different metric for a genuinely different
            kind of movement, not an inconsistency.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Legal note, unchanged from the Overview:</strong> exact
            nursery coordinates are sourced via the Google Places API,
            whose terms of service prohibit displaying that content on a
            non-Google map. Only the aggregated proximity contours are
            published; no nursery location is shown as a point anywhere on
            this site.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>6. Demographic classification <span class="step-ref">(ISTAT, step 1)</span></h2>
          <p>
            Quantile and Jenks natural breaks were tested in parallel;
            equal-interval classes were discarded early because they
            failed to surface any meaningful spatial variation in the
            underlying data.
          </p>
          <p><strong>Published thresholds (census-section resolution, static choropleths):</strong></p>
          <pre class="spec-block">Population under 5:     &lt; 2.2%    2.2–6.9%    6.9–22.2%    &gt; 22.2%
Population aged 25–45:  &lt; 10%     10–26%      26–56%       &gt; 56%</pre>
          <p>
            A correction for statistical instability in low-population
            census sections (small absolute numerators) was explored — a
            reliability threshold plus Jenks recalculated only on the
            filtered subset — but <strong>not applied</strong> to the
            published map. The historical process this case study
            documents (from 2025) didn't use that correction, and
            retroactively "fixing" the map would misrepresent what was
            actually decided at the time. The limitation is declared, not
            corrected.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>7. OMI rent estimation</h2>
          <p>
            Estimated monthly rent per zone = OMI price/m² × 80 m² (the
            family's target size) — a <strong>derived</strong> figure, not
            the raw OMI range, which is why it needs to be stated
            explicitly rather than left implicit.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Published thresholds:</strong> <code>&lt; €664</code>,
            <code>€664–784</code>, <code>€784–1,000</code>,
            <code>&gt; €1,000</code>.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>8. Interactive map <span class="step-ref">(step 5)</span> — data model and implementation notes</h2>
          <p>
            The interactive map aggregates all of the above to zone level.
            Schema per OMI zone:
          </p>
          <pre class="spec-block">zone_name       string
omi_class       "&lt;664" | "664-784" | "784-1000" | "&gt;1000"
under5_class    "&lt;3.1" | "3.1-3.4" | "3.4-3.6" | "&gt;3.6"
age2545_class   "&lt;21"  | "21-23"   | "23-25"    | "&gt;25"
commute_class   "&lt;200" | "200-210" | "210-220"  | "&gt;220"
shortlisted     boolean   (tag only, doesn't drive any map styling)</pre>
          <p>
            <strong>Threshold recalibration.</strong> The 
            <code> under5</code>/<code>age2545</code> thresholds above are
            <em> not</em> the same numbers as the static choropleths in
            section 6, and that's intentional, not a bug: aggregating
            fine-grained census-section data up to 47 coarser OMI zones
            compresses the observed range toward the mean. Reapplying the
            fine-grained thresholds as-is collapsed 46 of 47 zones into a
            single class — no visible signal. The interactive-map
            thresholds are quartiles recalculated on the actual
            OMI-zone-level distribution. Even recalibrated, the real
            spread is modest — roughly 2.8 percentage points for
            <code> under5</code> across all 47 zones — so the classes make
            the map legible; they don't manufacture a difference that
            isn't in the data. <code>commute_class</code> was
            <strong> not</strong> recalibrated: its relative dispersion was
            already low (coefficient of variation ≈ 3%), and round,
            communicable thresholds were preferred over statistically
            "balanced" cuts with no intuitive meaning.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Rendering constraint.</strong> Astro's scoped
            <code> &lt;style&gt;</code> blocks apply an attribute to
            elements present in the compiled template; elements created at
            runtime via <code>innerHTML</code> (the toolbar, legend, and
            detail panel here are all built in JS) never receive that
            attribute, so scoped rules silently don't match them — inline
            styles worked, scoped <code>width</code>/<code>height </code>
            didn't, producing an invisible 0×0 legend swatch until this
            was diagnosed. Fixed with <code>&lt;style is:global&gt; </code>
            on the component's whole style block, judged low collision
            risk given how specific its class names already are.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Initial view:</strong> anchored to
            <code> map.fitBounds()</code> over the real bounding box of the
            loaded zone geometries (40px padding), computed after fetching
            all four GeoJSON layers but before map creation — rather than
            a hand-picked center/zoom, which would need re-tuning by hand
            every time the data's extent changed.
          </p>
          <p class="callout">
            <strong>Limits, stated as of this writing:</strong> no
            keyboard alternative to clicking a zone (MapLibre doesn't
            expose polygons as focusable DOM elements); no
            <code> maxBounds</code>, so panning outside the data extent is
            possible even after the initial fit; performance with the
            full 47-zone dataset hasn't been stress-tested outside local
            development. And structurally: aggregating ISTAT's fine
            census-section demography up to OMI-zone granularity for this
            export is a real loss of spatial resolution compared to the
            static choropleths above — the same category of trade-off as
            the undirected road network and distance-not-time metric
            declared elsewhere on this page.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>9. Real monthly cost model <span class="step-ref">(step 7)</span></h2>
          <pre class="spec-block">price_total  = rent + condo_fee + utilities + parking
             + (property_tax + furnishing + deposit) / 12

cost_full    = price_total + nursery_cost_full_time
cost_part    = price_total + nursery_cost_part_time</pre>
          <p>
            One-off costs (furnishing, agency commission) are amortized
            over an assumed minimum one-year tenancy. Missing values are
            imputed with the mean across the candidate set.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Output:</strong> a relative index (100 = cheapest),
            computed separately per scenario rather than as one combined
            number — full-time and part-time rankings don't always agree.
            One concrete case in the dataset: an apartment ranked eighth
            under the full-time scenario overtakes the family's actual
            choice in cost-effectiveness under the part-time scenario. A
            single blended number would have hidden that.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>10. Custom basemap</h2>
          <p>
            No third-party basemap tiles anywhere on this site — CARTO's
            Dark Matter/Positron styles are free only for non-commercial
            use or approved "grantee" users, and a freelance-facing
            portfolio sits in a legal gray area there. Every map instead
            uses a basemap built from scratch with OSMnx:
          </p>
          <pre class="spec-block">water_tags = &#123;"natural": "water", "waterway": True&#125;
vegetation_tags = &#123;
    "natural": "wood",
    "landuse": ["forest", "meadow", "grass"],
    "leisure": "park",
&#125;</pre>
          <p>
            Line and polygon geometries are separated before export
            (<code>LineString</code> vs. <code>Polygon</code>/<code>MultiPolygon</code>)
            since OSMnx returns both under the same tag query. Hillshade
            (context map for the commute step, from SRTM):
          </p>
          <pre class="spec-block">Z factor:    1
Azimuth:     315°
Altitude:    45°
Opacity:     25–35%
Blend mode:  Multiply</pre>
        </article>

        <article class="step">
          <h2>11. Sources and attribution</h2>
          <pre class="spec-block">Road network / basemap:   © OpenStreetMap contributors
Elevation / hillshade:    U.S. Geological Survey (SRTM)
Demographics:              ISTAT (2021 census)
Real estate prices:        Agenzia delle Entrate – Osservatorio
                            del Mercato Immobiliare (OMI)</pre>
          <p>
            Google Places is deliberately not in this attribution block.
            It was the actual source for every nursery and service-POI
            record, but its terms of service don't permit displaying that
            content — including individual points — on a non-Google map.
            Rather than a citation, the constraint is stated directly
            wherever it's relevant (sections 4–5 above, and on the
            Overview page): only aggregate, derived outputs are ever
            published; no Places-sourced coordinate is shown as a point on
            this site.
          </p>
        </article>

      </section>
    </div>

    <a class="cta-button" href={`${base}/en/case-study-torino/`}>
      ← Back to the case study overview
    </a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-container {
    padding-left: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2cm);
    padding-top: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2cm);
    padding-bottom: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2cm);
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .page-container {
      padding-left: 1.5rem;
      padding-top: 1.5rem;
      padding-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
  .case-study {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-brass);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .case-hero h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
  }
  .intro, .step p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted-2);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .aside {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
  }
  .inline-link {
    color: var(--color-brass);
  }
  .step {
    margin: 2.5rem 0;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(198, 146, 20, 0.12);
  }
  .step h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
  }
  .step-ref {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }
  .callout {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    background: var(--color-ink-light);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-brass);
    padding: 0.85rem 1.1rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }
  .spec-block {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    background: var(--color-ink-light);
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 6px;
    overflow-x: auto;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }
  .spec-list {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted-2);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    padding-left: 1.4rem;
  }
  .spec-list li {
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .spec-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
  }
  .spec-table th,
  .spec-table td {
    padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
    text-align: left;
    vertical-align: top;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(159, 173, 185, 0.15);
  }
  .spec-table th {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--color-brass);
  }
  .spec-table td {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    color: var(--color-text-muted-2);
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .spec-table code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    color: var(--color-paper);
  }
  code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    color: var(--color-paper);
  }
  .cta-button {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    background: var(--color-brass);
    padding: 0.6rem 1.2rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-decoration: none;
    margin: 1rem 0 2rem;
  }
</style>
